<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="section5-2-summary">
  <title>Section 5.2 Summary</title>

  <p>This section introduced comparing several groups on a quantitative response using analysis of variance (ANOVA).</p>

  <p>ANOVA assesses whether differences among sample or treatment means are larger than expected from natural within-group variability. The procedure is based on the F distribution and applies both to independent random samples and randomized experiments, with conclusions depending on study design.</p>

  <p>You examined how ANOVA results depend on three key factors:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><p>How far apart the group means are.</p></li>
    <li><p>How much variation exists within groups.</p></li>
    <li><p>The group sample sizes.</p></li>
  </ul>

  <p>You also checked technical conditions for using the F model: independent observations (or random assignment), approximately normal group distributions, and similar group standard deviations.</p>

  <p>Example 5.2 provides an additional ANOVA application.</p>
</section>
